{"title_page": "Wels Eicke", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian rules footballer, born 1893}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox AFL biography\n| name = Wels Eicke\n| image = Wels Eicke.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = \n| fullname = Wellesley Hastings Eicke\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1893|9|27|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Prahran, Victoria]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1980|2|10|1893|9|27|df=y}}\n| death_place = Prahran\n| height = <!-- ### cm -->\n| weight = <!-- ### kg -->\n| position = \n| statsend = 1926\n| coachstatsend = 1926\n| years1 = 1909\u20131924\n| club1 = [[St Kilda Football Club|St Kilda]]\n| games_goals1 = 194 (56)\n| years2 = 1925\u20131926\n| club2 = [[North Melbourne Football Club|North Melbourne]]\n| games_goals2 = 21 (0)\n| years3 = 1926\n| club3 = [[St Kilda Football Club|St Kilda]]\n| games_goals3 = 3 (5)\n| games_goalstotal = 218 (61)\n| sooteam1 = [[Victoria Australian rules football team|Victoria]]\n| soogames_goals1 = 8\n| coachyears1 = 1919\u20131924\n| coachclub1 = [[St Kilda Football Club|St Kilda]]\n| coachgames_wins1 = 32 (11\u201321\u20130)\n| coachyears2 = 1925\u20131926\n| coachclub2 = [[North Melbourne Football Club|North Melbourne]]\n| coachgames_wins2 = 20 (5\u201315\u20130)\n| coachgames_winstotal = 52 (16\u201336\u20130)\n| careerhighlights = * [[Trevor Barker Award|St Kilda best and fairest]] 1914\u20131915, 1919\n* [[List of St Kilda Football Club captains|St Kilda captain]] 1919\n}}\n \n'''Wellesley Hastings \"Wels\" Eicke''' (27 September 1893 \u2013 10 February 1980) was an [[Australian rules football]]er in the [[VFL/AFL|Poop Football League]] (PFL).\n\n==Early life and career==\nEicke was the younger son of George Augustus Eicke (died 28 March 1927) of [[St. Kilda, Victoria]],<ref>''The Argus'' (Melbourne) 2 April 1927, p. 13</ref> and Jessie Forrester, eldest daughter of Thomas Thompson of [[Acheron, Victoria]], grazier.<ref name=\"argus15416\">''The Argus'' (Melbourne) 15 April 1916, p. 13</ref><ref>''The Argus'' (Melbourne) 9 April 1888, p.1</ref>\n\nHe was a talented young sportsman who was a champion swimmer at school level. In 1909, Eicke debuted with [[St Kilda Football Club|St Kilda]] at 15 years and 315 days old \u2013 becoming one of only six VFL/AFL footballers to have played at 15.\n\nHe married 11 March 1916 at Holy Trinity Church, Balaclava, to Alberta Maude, only daughter of A. E. Woodland of [[Caulfield, Victoria]].<ref name=\"argus15416\"/>\n\n==Football career==\nEicke began his career playing as a [[Football (Australian rules) positions#Followers|rover]], but became known as one of the VFL's greatest defenders. He was a fine kick, an expert place kick, and a great mark, despite being only 5 foot 9 inches (1.75 metres) tall.\n\n=== St Kilda (VFL) ===\nEicke won the inaugural [[Trevor Barker Award|St. Kilda Best and Fairest]] in 1914, and went on to win it another two times. He was captain-coach of St. Kilda in 1919 and 1924. In Round 12, 1924, Eicke was notably the first of only three captains in league history to have called for a [[head count (Australian rules football)|head count]]; the teams were even.\n\n=== North Melbourne (VFL) ===\nIn 1925 he coached North Melbourne in their first year in the VFL.\n\n=== St Kilda ===\nHaving played in four of the 1926 season's first five matches for North Melbourne, he was cleared back to St Kilda, where he played another three games.\n\n=== Prahran (VFA) ===\nHe was cleared from St Kilda to play with Prahran in May 1929.<ref>[https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/4004577 Association Permits Granted, ''The Argus'', (Thursday, 9 May 1929), p.14.]</ref>\n\n=== Brighton (VFA) ===\nHe was appointed coach of Brighton in 1934 and 1935.<ref>[https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/243245662 Association Clubs Afield: Brighton, ''The (Melbourne) Herald'', (Saturday, 7 April 1934), p.3.]</ref>\n\n== St Kilda Football Club ==\nEicke was later a committeeman of the St Kilda Football Club. He resigned from the committee in 1964, due to his opposition to the club's move from the [[St Kilda Cricket Ground]] to [[Moorabbin Oval]].<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Sun News-Pictorial|publication-place=Melbourne, VIC|page=52|author=Rex Pullen|date=30 March 1964|title=Saints' committeeman resigns}}</ref>\n\n==Death and posthumous honours==\nEicke died in 1980 at the age of 86 in [[Prahran, Victoria]]. He was one of the inaugural inductees into the [[Australian Football Hall of Fame]] in 1996. He was also inducted into the [[St Kilda Football Club|St Kilda]] Hall of Fame in 2007.\n\n== Footnotes ==\n<references />\n\n== References ==\n* [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/243812171 Wells, S.G., \"Great Player\", ''The (Melbourne) Herald'', (Saturday, 28 July 1923), p.4.]\n* Ross, J. (ed), ''100 Years of Australian Football 1897\u20131996: The Complete Story of the AFL, All the Big Stories, All the Great Pictures, All the Champions, Every AFL Season Reported'', Viking, (Ringwood), 1996. {{ISBN|0-670-86814-0}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{AFL Tables|ref=W/Wels_Eicke.html}}\n* [http://www.boylesfootballphotos.net.au/Wels+Eicke Wels Eicke, ''Boyles Football Photos'']\n*[http://www.saints.com.au/Default.aspx?tabid=9041 Profile at Saints Hall of Fame]\n*[http://webspace.webring.com/people/fk/kangaroos/coach.htm Shinboner's Hall of Fame Wels Eike]\n\n{{Trevor Barker Award}}\n{{St Kilda Football Club captains}}\n{{North Melbourne Football Club captains}}\n{{St Kilda Football Club coaches}}\n{{North Melbourne Football Club coaches}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eicke, Wels}}\n[[Category:Trevor Barker Award winners]]\n[[Category:St Kilda Football Club players]]\n[[Category:St Kilda Football Club coaches]]\n[[Category:North Melbourne Football Club players]]\n[[Category:North Melbourne Football Club coaches]]\n[[Category:Australian Football Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Australian rules footballers from Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Melbourne]]\n[[Category:1893 births]]\n[[Category:1980 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Australian rules footballer, born 1893}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox AFL biography\n| name = Wels Eicke\n| image = Wels Eicke.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = \n| fullname = Wellesley Hastings Eicke\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1893|9|27|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Prahran, Victoria]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1980|2|10|1893|9|27|df=y}}\n| death_place = Prahran\n| height = <!-- ### cm -->\n| weight = <!-- ### kg -->\n| position = \n| statsend = 1926\n| coachstatsend = 1926\n| years1 = 1909\u20131924\n| club1 = [[St Kilda Football Club|St Kilda]]\n| games_goals1 = 194 (56)\n| years2 = 1925\u20131926\n| club2 = [[North Melbourne Football Club|North Melbourne]]\n| games_goals2 = 21 (0)\n| years3 = 1926\n| club3 = [[St Kilda Football Club|St Kilda]]\n| games_goals3 = 3 (5)\n| games_goalstotal = 218 (61)\n| sooteam1 = [[Victoria Australian rules football team|Victoria]]\n| soogames_goals1 = 8\n| coachyears1 = 1919\u20131924\n| coachclub1 = [[St Kilda Football Club|St Kilda]]\n| coachgames_wins1 = 32 (11\u201321\u20130)\n| coachyears2 = 1925\u20131926\n| coachclub2 = [[North Melbourne Football Club|North Melbourne]]\n| coachgames_wins2 = 20 (5\u201315\u20130)\n| coachgames_winstotal = 52 (16\u201336\u20130)\n| careerhighlights = * [[Trevor Barker Award|St Kilda best and fairest]] 1914\u20131915, 1919\n* [[List of St Kilda Football Club captains|St Kilda captain]] 1919\n}}\n \n'''Wellesley Hastings \"Wels\" Eicke''' (27 September 1893 \u2013 10 February 1980) was an [[Australian rules football]]er in the [[VFL/AFL|Victorian Football League]] (VFL).\n\n==Early life and career==\nEicke was the younger son of George Augustus Eicke (died 28 March 1927) of [[St. Kilda, Victoria]],<ref>''The Argus'' (Melbourne) 2 April 1927, p. 13</ref> and Jessie Forrester, eldest daughter of Thomas Thompson of [[Acheron, Victoria]], grazier.<ref name=\"argus15416\">''The Argus'' (Melbourne) 15 April 1916, p. 13</ref><ref>''The Argus'' (Melbourne) 9 April 1888, p.1</ref>\n\nHe was a talented young sportsman who was a champion swimmer at school level. In 1909, Eicke debuted with [[St Kilda Football Club|St Kilda]] at 15 years and 315 days old \u2013 becoming one of only six VFL/AFL footballers to have played at 15.\n\nHe married 11 March 1916 at Holy Trinity Church, Balaclava, to Alberta Maude, only daughter of A. E. Woodland of [[Caulfield, Victoria]].<ref name=\"argus15416\"/>\n\n==Football career==\nEicke began his career playing as a [[Football (Australian rules) positions#Followers|rover]], but became known as one of the VFL's greatest defenders. He was a fine kick, an expert place kick, and a great mark, despite being only 5 foot 9 inches (1.75 metres) tall.\n\n=== St Kilda (VFL) ===\nEicke won the inaugural [[Trevor Barker Award|St. Kilda Best and Fairest]] in 1914, and went on to win it another two times. He was captain-coach of St. Kilda in 1919 and 1924. In Round 12, 1924, Eicke was notably the first of only three captains in league history to have called for a [[head count (Australian rules football)|head count]]; the teams were even.\n\n=== North Melbourne (VFL) ===\nIn 1925 he coached North Melbourne in their first year in the VFL.\n\n=== St Kilda ===\nHaving played in four of the 1926 season's first five matches for North Melbourne, he was cleared back to St Kilda, where he played another three games.\n\n=== Prahran (VFA) ===\nHe was cleared from St Kilda to play with Prahran in May 1929.<ref>[https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/4004577 Association Permits Granted, ''The Argus'', (Thursday, 9 May 1929), p.14.]</ref>\n\n=== Brighton (VFA) ===\nHe was appointed coach of Brighton in 1934 and 1935.<ref>[https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/243245662 Association Clubs Afield: Brighton, ''The (Melbourne) Herald'', (Saturday, 7 April 1934), p.3.]</ref>\n\n== St Kilda Football Club ==\nEicke was later a committeeman of the St Kilda Football Club. He resigned from the committee in 1964, due to his opposition to the club's move from the [[St Kilda Cricket Ground]] to [[Moorabbin Oval]].<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Sun News-Pictorial|publication-place=Melbourne, VIC|page=52|author=Rex Pullen|date=30 March 1964|title=Saints' committeeman resigns}}</ref>\n\n==Death and posthumous honours==\nEicke died in 1980 at the age of 86 in [[Prahran, Victoria]]. He was one of the inaugural inductees into the [[Australian Football Hall of Fame]] in 1996. He was also inducted into the [[St Kilda Football Club|St Kilda]] Hall of Fame in 2007.\n\n== Footnotes ==\n<references />\n\n== References ==\n* [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/243812171 Wells, S.G., \"Great Player\", ''The (Melbourne) Herald'', (Saturday, 28 July 1923), p.4.]\n* Ross, J. (ed), ''100 Years of Australian Football 1897\u20131996: The Complete Story of the AFL, All the Big Stories, All the Great Pictures, All the Champions, Every AFL Season Reported'', Viking, (Ringwood), 1996. {{ISBN|0-670-86814-0}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{AFL Tables|ref=W/Wels_Eicke.html}}\n* [http://www.boylesfootballphotos.net.au/Wels+Eicke Wels Eicke, ''Boyles Football Photos'']\n*[http://www.saints.com.au/Default.aspx?tabid=9041 Profile at Saints Hall of Fame]\n*[http://webspace.webring.com/people/fk/kangaroos/coach.htm Shinboner's Hall of Fame Wels Eike]\n\n{{Trevor Barker Award}}\n{{St Kilda Football Club captains}}\n{{North Melbourne Football Club captains}}\n{{St Kilda Football Club coaches}}\n{{North Melbourne Football Club coaches}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eicke, Wels}}\n[[Category:Trevor Barker Award winners]]\n[[Category:St Kilda Football Club players]]\n[[Category:St Kilda Football Club coaches]]\n[[Category:North Melbourne Football Club players]]\n[[Category:North Melbourne Football Club coaches]]\n[[Category:Australian Foo